(2, 5, 'german-films', 'German Films', '<p><span class="whiteheader">German Films </span></p>\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<p><em>A selection of films from the German competition at the 2009 interfilm Berlin Short Film Festival.</em><br />\n</p>\n<br />\n<p>\nTHE PALACE GEORGE CINEMAS</p>\n<p class="uppercase">133-135 fitzroy st, st kilda <br />\n</p>\nWEDNESDAY 26 MAY, 7.30PM - 9PM<br />\n<br />\nEach year interfilm Berlin receives around 800 entries for its German competition. This selection of fiction, documentary and animation from the 2009 Festival provides a snapshot of contemporary German short production and includes the Titelbild Award winning<em> Bes</em>.<br />\n<br />\n<p>\nCurated by: Alexander Stein, Sophie Werner and Matthias Groll – interfilm Berlin Short Film Festival</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2010-04-23 12:08:18', '2010-05-18 09:19:26'),
(3, 5, 'dutch-films', 'Dutch Films', '<p><span class="whiteheader">Dutch Films</span></p>\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<p><em>A selection of films from the ‘Focus On: the Netherlands’ program at the 2009 interfilm Berlin Short Film Festival</em><br />\n</p>\n<br />\n<p><span class="uppercase">The Palace George Cinemas</span></p>\n<p class="uppercase">133-135 fitzroy st, st kilda <br />\n</p>\n<span class="uppercase">\n</span>SUNDAY 30 MAY, 4.30PM - 6PM<br />\n<br />\nThe Netherlands has a rich history of diverse filmmaking, encompassing socially analytical documentaries, colourful animations and moving dramas. This program includes the 2009 Berlin-Brandenburg Short Award Best Film winner, <em>Missen/Missing</em>, as well as the winner of the interfilm Documentary Prize, <em>Grijsgedraaid/Grey Matter</em>. <br />\n<br />\n<p>Curated by: Romy Albers and&nbsp; Maike Lasseur – Film Museum Amsterdam</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2010-04-23 12:08:29', '2010-05-18 09:20:20'),
(4, 5, 'berlin-the-wall-beyond', 'Berlin: The wall & Beyond', '<p class="whiteheader">BERLIN: THE WALL AND BEYOND</p>\n<hr size="2" width="100%" />\n<p><em>&nbsp;A selection of films from the ‘CLOSE UP - Eastern Front / Western Front’ program at interfilm Berlin 2009 Short Film Festival – marking the 20th anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall</em><br />\n<br />\n</p>\n<p>\nTHE PALACE GEORGE CINEMAS</p>\n<p class="uppercase">133-135 fitzroy st, st kilda<br />\n</p>\n<p>\nFRIDAY 28 MAY, 7.30PM - 9PM<br />\n<br />\nThe Berlin Wall marked a manacing borderline that cut through the city for 28 years; freedom and democracy on one side, social achievements and proletariat dictatorship on the other. It symbolised both the division of Germany as well as the state that entrenched itself behind it. &nbsp;<br />\n</p>\n<p>\n</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>This program follows the different strategies of truth and conviction during the existance of GDR and beyond the time the Wall fell. The films deal with the power and powerlessness of both the Stasi (Ministerium f&#252;r Staatssicherheit/ Ministry for State Security - East German Secret Police) and individual people. </p>\n<p>\n<br />\n&nbsp;</p>', '2010-04-23 12:08:54', '2010-05-18 09:19:02'),
